IaC  ---  Terraform, Pulumi
with the help of IaC tool ---> its has the templates with contains your
infrastructure specifications, easy to manage and edit it and also
distribute configuration to other teams
Benefits:

Cost reduction
Increase in speed of deployment
Reduce Human errors
Improve the infra consitency (Idempotent)
Eliminates the configuration drifts

state file ---> Timestamp, Who did the changes, on which files




2 Approaches / methods
Declarative Method

Iac (Terraform), what is your requirement ( needs )
10 server - 32GB Ram, 16 VCPU's
Storage - 100 GB
In declarative method you only need to define the desire final condiction
of the infrastructure without going in details and without even mentioned
how it is achieved. it allow the Terraform to handle itself

Imperative methods --->
you to define the sepecific step by step commands to achieve the required configuration.

Power shell /Bash shell scripting, Python
Ansible server ---> modules ---> AWS, Azure, GCP, few other cloud env

Here in imperative you need to very much detailed, you need provide all
the detail to create infra and it would be complex configurations.
You need a high level skilled person to write the scripts/configuration
files.

Provisioning Vs Configuration Management

Provisioning:
It is process of setting up IT infrastructure
(VM, Storage, Network, LB, Databases), access to these resources to end user
and make them to be available
Configuration Management --->
it comes after the provisioning and it means installing the software,
configuring the server and maintaining them.
Ansible, Chef, Puppet, Saltstack

Mutable and Immutable infrastructure:

Tools can also differ by the type of infra they are building, Mutable or
it could immutable
Shifting from one to another is costly and heavy on operations, so
carefully consider your needs.

Mutable Infra

Mutable infra can be changed to fix your bussiness needs, you need to
introduce the updates to the existing application or software versions,
patches and scaling in the same server. reverting back the changes is
quite challenging and usally it is not recommended, if you are doing a
changes in the same server, you might drift from the configuration as
well there could be security issues.

